Daily Standup Meeting: 9 March 2026  
Project: Mobile Car Recovery Management System  
Sprint: 1 | Time: 10:30 am  
Attendance: Avisha Garusingha, Zion James-Simpson, Hoang Nguyen, Brent Li, Shrayesh Lawaju.

The second standup meeting focused on the formal selection of the data structure and initial design requirements. Avisha Garusingha (Team Leader) opened the session by confirming that the GitHub repository was now correctly configured with a .gitignore file to prevent unnecessary build files from being tracked. She reminded the team that iterative progress must be clearly demonstrated through regular commits to meet the project management criteria.

Brent Li (Developer) led the technical discussion by formally proposing the use of a custom-built Binary Search Tree (BST) to manage the car recovery records. He explained that this would enable the team to meet the strict "No STL" constraint while still providing an efficient method for storing and retrieving data. Hoang Nguyen (Developer) supported this choice, noting that a BST would allow the group to demonstrate a theoretical search time complexity of $O(\log n)$ in the final report, which is significantly better than a simple linear search through an array.

Zion James-Simpson (Secretary) spent the session taking notes on these technical justifications.
He has begun drafting the "Appropriate Selection of Data Structure" section of the technical report, ensuring the team’s reasoning is documented while it is fresh.
Shrayesh Lawaju (Tester) updated the team on the testing strategy. He has drafted a set of initial test cases focusing on the BST’s core functionality, such as inserting a new car record and searching for both existing and non-existent registration plates.
Shrayesh mentioned that he is considering how to structure the unit tests to match the testing approach that will be described in the final report, ensuring consistency between the code and the documentation.
The team identified a potential obstacle: the risk of the BST becoming unbalanced if data is entered in a specific order, which would degrade performance to $O(n)$. It was agreed that the developers would investigate simple ways to mitigate this during the implementation phase. The meeting concluded with the team feeling confident 
















